Date: Mon, 13 May 2002 09:20:25 +1200
From: Howard Pharo <PharoH@maf.govt.nz>
Foot & mouth disease - S. Korea
--------------------------------
Given that pig herds are most likely to become infected with FMD virus by
ingestion of contaminated meat (e.g. garbage containing meat that is
contaminated with the virus), investigators would do well to concentrate
their efforts on legally or illegally imported meat when trying to track
down the route of introduction of this virus [see Pharo HJ, Foot-and-mouth
disease: an assessment of the risks facing New Zealand. NZ Vet J 50(2)
46-55, 2002].
In the past there have been various unofficial reports of vast smuggling
operations involving meat and live animals from PRC to neighboring
countries (e.g. to Taiwan by Croddy in ProMED-mail 20010501.0847), but
instead of discussing the likelihood of such high-risk routes we often hear
only speculation of spread by wind, straw, hay, sugar cane tops, human
feet, and even horses hooves. Meanwhile it is rare for the actual source of
the virus to be identified.
From a risk analyst's perspective, there is an urgent need for experiments
to be carried out to evaluate the FMD risk posed by the fomites listed above.
--
Howard J Pharo
National Adviser, Risk Analysis
Animal Biosecurity
MAF Biosecurity Authority
